docs.abstract: The case of Sun Shihua, a female lawyer who described being beaten and forced to submit to a strip search in Guangzhou, has prompted a debate about discrimination against women.
docs.snippet: The case of Sun Shihua, a female lawyer who described being beaten and forced to submit to a strip search in Guangzhou, has prompted a debate about discrimination against women.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — One late September afternoon, Sun Shihua, a lawyer, walked into a police station in southern China for a routine visit with a client.

headline.main: Account of Police Brutality Gives Rise to a #MeToo Moment in China
headline.print_headline: Charges Of Abuse Stir Debate In China

byline.original: By Javier C. Hernández and Zoe Mou

docs.abstract: The ideological bent of those overseeing collegiate life is having the biggest impact on campus culture.
docs.snippet: The ideological bent of those overseeing collegiate life is having the biggest impact on campus culture.
docs.lead_paragraph: I received a disconcerting email this year from a senior staff member in the Office of Diversity and Campus Engagement at Sarah Lawrence College, where I teach. The email was soliciting ideas from the Sarah Lawrence community for a conference, open to all of us, titled “Our Liberation Summit.” The conference would touch on such progressive topics as liberation spaces on campus, Black Lives Matter and justice for women as well as for lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, queer, intersex, asexual and allied people.

headline.main: Think Professors Are Liberal? Try School Administrators

docs.abstract: Officer Timothy Loehmann fatally shot Tamir, 12, at a park in 2014. The shooting added to national outrage over the killing of unarmed black men and boys by law enforcement.
docs.snippet: Officer Timothy Loehmann fatally shot Tamir, 12, at a park in 2014. The shooting added to national outrage over the killing of unarmed black men and boys by law enforcement.
docs.lead_paragraph: A former Cleveland patrol officer who fatally shot Tamir Rice, a 12-year-old boy whose death in 2014 intensified national outrage over the killing of unarmed black men and boys, has been hired by a police department in a small Ohio village.

headline.main: Cleveland Officer Who Killed Tamir Rice Is Hired by an Ohio Police Department
headline.print_headline: Cleveland Officer Who Killed 12-Year-Old Is Hired for an Ohio Force
